Ask HN: The ML/AI space is overwhelmingly large. Where to start?
text: I'm a "traditional" software engineer with many years of experience in web technologies. I feel fascinated by ML/AI technologies, but I don't know where to begin to learn about it. I am also not even sure yet if it's something I would enjoy, so I want to find the best way to maximize my investment of time vs return in experience and skill. I am specifically interested in computer vision and natural language processing. Where should I begin? Is Andrew Ng's course still a good starting point? Or the D2L.ai course?

Show HN: Despise the all-in-one world as much as me? Micro-Tool Strategy
text:
Hey Everyone, I'm new to the community but I'm curious about the collective opinion of all-in-one tools. Whether it be in development, marketing, sales industries

I myself had set out long ago to build a specific marketing tool with my brother (software engineer) but it quickly fell into the all-in-one style of tool. We've recently pivoted to actively avoid and provide the opposite.

I had asked my team of marketers about how they search for answers to basic questions. Whether it's SEO, social, ads, etc. they all collectively agreed that they will avoid any tooling and opt for the immediate value option. Any sort of tradeoff, templates, or related resource.

I thought I'd pop on here and see if the community was willing to either put this idea to rest or support this search pattern.

We have since started developing things to appeal to this type of marketer. Quick value coupled with an extremely obvious search. I don't mean to push for traffic but to contextualize this idea we created a testimonial creator (https://testimonial-creator.tactycs.io/landing) which follows exactly what's mentioned above. Immediate value, free components, no hiding behind all in one massive features.

All of this to ask, does the community prefer an all-in-one solution or smaller, obvious solutions to specific questions/challenges?

Appreciate all feedback on the question above or any thoughts of the early access tool! Cheers everyone.
